[normal]Witness: 
[normal]Brandon Lewis MP[bold], Parliamentary Under Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, gave evidence.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Chair:[bold] Minister, once again welcome to our Committee, to a one
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]off evidence session on the local government finance settlement.  Part of the stimulus for the 
[normal]session
[normal] came from quite a large number of petitions, which the Committee eventually received, about the perceived imbalance in the allocation of money to rural areas, so some of our questions will focus on that, but then we will look more widely at the settlement as well.  Just to make sure we get everything on the record, it is appropriate right at the beginning of a session—I think it will do for both sessions—if Members put their interests on the record as well.  I am a Vice
[normal]-P
[normal]resident of the Local Government Association.  
[normal]Could
[normal] anyone else with a particular interest related to local government put their interest on the record
[normal]?
[normal]Mrs [bold]Glindon[bold]:[bold] My husband is a councillor in 
[normal]North Tyneside
[normal].
[normal]Chris Williamson:[bold] I have got a couple of staff who are elected members.
[normal]David [bold]Heyes[bold]:[bold] Me too.
[normal]Simon Danczuk:[bold] My wife is a councillor, my father-in-law is a councillor, and some of my staff are councillors.  
[normal]Heather Wheeler:[bold] I am a Vice
[normal]-Presid
[normal]ent of the LGA and my husband is leader of a council.
[normal]John Pugh:[bold] I have a member of staff who is a councillor.
[normal]Mrs [bold]Glindon[bold]:[bold] 
[normal]I 
[normal]have a member of staff who is a councillor.  
[normal]Chair:[bold] Is that our lot?  Thank you very much.  Thank you, Minister, once again for joining us.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q1 [bold]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Mrs [bold]Glindon[bold]:[bold] Good afternoon, Minister.  Do you support the Rural Fair Share campaign for the rural penalty to be reduced from 50% to 40% by 2020?
[normal]Brandon Lewis[bold]: We do not agree with their figures, in the sense of the way they calculate the 50% and 40%.  
[normal]To compare
[normal] like-for-like authorities, if you look at unitary authorities, in 2014-2015, the difference is about 10%; if you look at the shire district areas, in 2014-2015 it will be 12%; if you look at fire and rescue authorities, it will be about minus 3%; and for county councils, it will be about 4%.  That is because the way they assess what is a rural area is quite different 
[normal]from 
[normal]the way we do.  In a simplistic sense—I can give you a colloquial example of this—the way they look at the rural definition, they would include 
[normal]Norfolk
[normal] as a rural county.  I can see the logic of that, but those of us who live in Great Yarmouth, 
[normal]Norwich
[normal] and 
[normal]King’s Lynn
[normal] would be 
[normal]the 
[normal]first to admit we 
[normal]are predominantly urban and we have deprived areas and areas of high density as well.  When we distribute funding at DCLG, we do it in different ways.  We would class 
[normal]Norfolk
[normal] as North Norfolk, Mid
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]Norfolk
[normal], 
[normal]Broadland
[normal], 
[normal]Breckland
[normal] and South West Norfolk, not 
[normal]Norwich
[normal] or Great Yarmouth or 
[normal]King’s Lynn
[normal], so it is quite a different way of calculating it.  I have
[normal] had this conversation with SPARSE themselves. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q2 [bold]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Mrs [bold]Glindon[bold]:[bold] With regard to what you said on that, is there a reason why you did not take notice of the 
[normal]call for the 
[normal]Efficiency Support for 
[normal]S
[normal]ervices in 
[normal]S
[normal]parse 
[normal]A
[normal]reas funding to be 
[normal]increased to £30 
[normal]million when Graham Stuart MP asked for that?
[normal]Brandon Lewis[bold]: We put
[normal] £8.5 
[normal]million in last year.  This year, in the settlement as it currently stands, that is at
[normal] £9.5 
[normal]million and we are going 
[normal]to roll it into the base,
[normal] because we do recognise—we have been quite clear about this—that there is a gap between rural and urban.  But, as I say, as far as we are concerned, it is not 50% narrowing to 40% in the first place, so to have a discussion 
[normal]around £30 
[normal]million would be presuming a set of figures that we do not agree with in the first place.  As I say, if you look at it like for like, for 2014-2015 the gap 
[normal]ranges from a maximum of 12% down to minus 3% for the fire authorities.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q3 [bold]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Mrs [bold]Glindon[bold]:[bold] Do you think that the 
[normal]ESSSA
[normal] 
[normal]is just a temporary fix—a political fix—or do you think it is evidence that the Government and your Department accept there is a rural penalty that needs to be reduced?
[normal]Brandon Lewis[bold]: As I said just now, we do agree that there is a gap.  We 
[normal]were sympathetic to the argument
[normal], and that is why we put the extra money in last year.  We have increased that money to
[normal] £9.5 
[normal]million this year and we have put it in the baseline so that it is not just a one-off; it is rolled into the baseline.  We are dealing with that.  In that sense we have recognised the issue and dealt with it.  Having said that, I also need to be quite clear 
[normal]that 
[normal]there is limited evidence of there being considerable extra cost—which some people would argue—of dealing with rural services.  The Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs has commissioned some work, which we are working with them on, to have a look at this very issue, as it happens.  That will be reporting back later this year and, depending on the findings—and I am not going to pre-judge 
[normal]that; the work is only being commissioned in February or March
[normal]—that may well give everybody something to look at for the next settlement.  But at the moment, as I say, the gap for local authorities ranges from 12% to 4%.  It is not a very big gap 
[normal]now.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q4 [bold]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Mrs [bold]Glindon[bold]:[bold] There is a big difference between the amount that the Rural Fair Share petition
[normal] are asking for—£30 
[normal]million—and that which the Government is saying it will give, so there must be
[normal] some cause for concern that is justified.
[normal]Brandon Lewis[bold]: No.  As I said, the difference between the figures is the difference between the 12% and the 40% or 50% that you mentioned in the opening question.  That is because of the way that they are assessing what is a rural area.  As I say, they would class the whole of Norfolk, when in fact there are towns and districts and authorities in Norfolk that are predominantly urban, if not entirely urban, such as, as I said, Norwich, King’s Lynn and Great Yarmouth.  In terms of how we fund, they are not classed as predominantly rural areas.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q5 [bold]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Mrs [bold]Glindon[bold]:[bold] 
[normal]Is the 
[normal]purpose of revenue support to ensure that everybody would receive the same level of 
[normal]local 
[normal]service if they were paying a notional uniform council tax across the board?
[normal]Brandon Lewis[bold]: The idea of every single person in the country paying the same council tax would be an interesting thing to take forward, and some councils might have different views on that to others.  The money 
[normal]that is distributed through grant predominantly—and obviously the most deprived areas get the highest amount of grant—is in order to make sure they can provide 
[normal]the core services.  Depending on where you are, different councils will make decisions on what their primary focus is and what their priorities are.  I have said to this Committee before everybody expects to have their waste collected—the Secretary of State would argue vehemently that it should be on a weekly basis—and to have the streets kept clean, but the priorities for an individual authority are a matter for the local authority.  That is localism.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q6 [bold]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Mrs [bold]Glindon[bold]:[bold] So there would be different problems in urban and, perhaps, rural areas.
[normal]Brandon Lewis[bold]: I am sure some local authorities would argue that there are not only different issues to deal with in a rural area compared to an urban area, which is undoubtedly true.  In an urban area you are dealing with density of population but in close proximity to each other, generally, because of how it is built up; a more rural area will be dealing with higher transport costs or gaps and differences between areas and villages.  Equally, you will find rural areas will make the point, depending on where they are and their proximity to the next town, that they are dealing with different issues according to their area—and the same with urban areas.  I have two of the most deprived wards in the country in my constituency.  Great 
[normal]Yarmouth
[normal] would make the point that they have very different issues to deal with 
[normal]from 
[normal] some of the areas in the 
[normal]Midlands
[normal] and the North, partly because they are a seaside town, partly because some of it is rural
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]Parts of 
[normal]Norfolk
[normal] 
[normal]would argue there are
[normal] 
[normal]areas of 
[normal]rural deprivation.  It is quite difficult to say that rural is just different 
[normal]from
[normal] urban and all rural is the same.  One of the beauties of our country is wherever you go there is something unique and something different, and that gives a different challenge to that authority.  It is also why that power for local authorities to make their own priorities is so important
[normal],
[normal] because they know what they need to deliver most for their local residents.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q7 [bold]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Could I just turn Mary’s 
[normal]important 
[normal]question around a little bit?   Is the principle of the grant settlement that it equalises out differences in needs and differences in resources between authorities, to the extent that if everyone were to pay the same level of council tax, they would get the same level of service?
[normal]Brandon Lewis[bold]: Do not forget the whole structure of how we finance local government is changing.  The basic baseline—for want of a better phrase—has the banding in; it has the four bands
[normal],
[normal] which does recognise that.  That is why some authorities will be more grant-dependent than others, so they get that basic funding to be able to 
[normal]provide basic services.  But we have moved to a whole new way of funding local government through the business
[normal] 
[normal]rates retention scheme and the New Homes Bonus.  We are moving away from a system that is grant-dependent to a system where local authorities are incentivised to do things.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q8 [bold]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] So that principle has been eroded, effectively.
[normal]Brandon Lewis[bold]: Yes, there is a big shift away from the begging-bowl structure of the past to an incentive-based structure for the future.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q9 [bold]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Mark [bold]Pawsey[bold]:[bold] Minister, can I follow up the concerns of rural communities that Mary has just spoken to you about and particularly ask you about the 
[normal]sparsity
[normal] ratings, or the 
[normal]sparsity
[normal] allowance?  T
[normal]he sum of £200 
[normal]million was put on one side to reflect that, but then damping provisions were introduced, which meant that three
[normal]-
[normal]quarters of it would not get out to the local authorities.  Was it the Department’s intention to effectively give with one hand and then take away with the other?
[normal]Brandon Lewis[bold]: First of all, 
[normal]not every authority—to the point you made, Mr 
[normal]Pawsey
[normal]—was detrimentally affected.  Technically, you will find some examples of rural authorities 
[normal]that 
[normal]ge
[normal]t the benefit of the extra £9.5 
[normal]million and benefit from damping.  It depends on where you sit on the
[normal] scale.  The decision that was made in late 2012 for the settlement for 2013-2014 put damping in and widened and stretched the bands to make sure there was more protection in there for the most grant-dependent authorities, because there was recognition that although there is a gap between rural and urban—and I have to say
[normal] 
[normal]this is underlining the fundamental difference between the 50% argument and 
[normal]our 
[normal]12%
[normal] 
[normal]at-
[normal]worst-this-
[normal]year argument—the most grant-dependent authorities, which tend to be in some of the most deprived areas, needed that extra protection to make sure they had the basic funding
[normal].  It also avoided
[normal] volatility for the business-rates scheme.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q10 [bold]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Mark [bold]Pawsey[bold]:[bold] I accept that.  You 
[normal]have said that we will look at the situation today and there will be no assessment until 2020.  Is that
[normal] still the case?  You spoke just earlier about looking at a report later this year.  Will that change things, or is that a separate issue?
[normal]Brandon Lewis[bold]: There are two different things going on.  The business
[normal] 
[normal]rates retention scheme is locked in until 2020, and if we unlock that, then we start 
[normal]disincentivising
[normal] the growth opportunities through th
[normal]at
[normal] scheme.  However, the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs are doing some work 
[normal]on 
[normal]the issues for rural areas.  Our Department is working with them on that.  That work will be done over the summer; it is due to report back in the autumn.  I am not for a moment saying that there will be things in that that we need to look 
[normal]at, because we do not know what is in the report yet; it would be pre-judging it.  The SPARSE argument is that there are big differences in the ability or the cost of providing services in rural areas as opposed to urban.  If that report backs that up, it will be the first time realistically there has been solid evidence to back that case up, and then the Government will have to have a look at that.  However, at the moment, that evidence does not exist, and we do not know quite what that report will feed back.  
[normal]T
[normal]he 
[normal]movements
[normal] 
[normal]we 
[normal]are
[normal] able to look at
[normal]—for 
[normal]ex
[normal]ample, this year, with the £9.5 
[normal]million
[normal]—give 
[normal]us some flexibility, but, again, I would underwrite 
[normal]that 
[normal]and say
[normal],
[normal] if you look at like-for-like authorities, the worst gap is only 12%.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q11 [bold]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Mark [bold]Pawsey[bold]:[bold] But you are saying to those authorities who feel that they have not done particularly well this year that it does not necessarily mean that there can be no changes between now and 2020, because this report may provide the evidence they need, in which case the Government will act.
[normal]Brandon Lewis[bold]: From their point of view, if that report provides evidence, then it is a very strong piece of argument for them to put to the Government.  There is a track record of 
[normal]our
[normal] looking year to year at what we need to do to make sure we get the settlement in the right place.  For exam
[normal]ple, last year, we put the £8.5 
[normal]million in; this 
[normal]year, we put £9.5 
[normal]million in.  Last year, we had the de 
[normal]minimis
[normal] for some authorities—the lowest quartile of charges.  There have been variations and flexibilities quite regularly within settlements.  I am not pre-judging what may or may not happen next year, but certainly in the past there is evidence that, where there needs to be flexibility, the Government will look at it.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q12 [bold]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Mark [bold]Pawsey[bold]:[bold] So there will be a regular review.  One of the great concerns is that there is a bi
[normal]t of a cliff face coming. 
[normal] 
[normal]I
[normal]f there is a perceived unfairness now, the Government are not going to do anything about it until 2020
[normal]; i
[normal]f there is a review in 2020, there could be then significant change.  How will local authorities prepare for that?  Or will Government simply 
[normal]defer yet again?  How can you
[normal] reassure authorities that that is not going to happen?
[normal]Brandon Lewis[bold]: I might be going a bit beyond my remit to pre-judge what a Government in 2020 might do, because technically I could be binding the Government after next, just about, depending when in 2020 we are talking about.
[normal]Mark [bold]Pawsey[bold]:[bold] But you understand 
[normal]the concerns.  
[normal]Brandon Lewis[bold]: I do understand the point, but to make the business
[normal] 
[normal]rates retention scheme properly able to incentivise, there needed to be 
[normal]a baseline, and then beyond that, that growth allows the councils to benefit.  The view was that to lock that in until 2020 was the logical thing, bearing in mind the baseline does recognise the banded floors in the first place.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q13 [bold]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Chris Williamson:[bold] You have probably heard that the Rural Services Network has complained that authorities in the Home Counties have seen the smallest reductions in settlement funding during 2013-2014 through to 2015-2016.  People are asking why these affluent areas are being given an easier ride than more deprived rural and urban local authorities.
[normal]Brandon Lewis[bold]: I would argue they are not, in the sense that the most deprived 10% of authorities have a spending power that averages just over £3,000, whereas the 
[normal]least deprived 
[normal]10% have a spending power of £1,952.  They have a much higher starting point in the first place.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q14 [bold]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Chris Williamson:[bold] The indicative figures for 2015-2016 suggest that there is going to be a 0.6% increase for South East England but a 2% reduction for 
[normal]England
[normal] as a whole.  I just wondered how you thought th
[normal]at can be fair.
[normal]Brandon Lewis[bold]: There were about 40 authorities that had an increase last year; there are some this year; and there will no doubt be some next year.  That potentially could grow.  Those authorities who had those increases had them because
[normal] 
[normal]of the New Homes Bonus.  It is proving the incentive is working; they are building the house
[normal]s and they are getting the money.  As the business
[normal] 
[normal]rates retention scheme works and as we start to see economic growth, there is a real potential some authorities will see growth through that as well.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q15 [bold]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Chris Williamson:[bold] Can you understand, though, why some people think that the Government 
[normal]is 
[normal]in some ways rigging the situation in favour of more affluent parts of the country, whichever measure you look at, whether it be spending power or grant settlement?  
[normal]F
[normal]or example—and this is often an example that is cited—the Prime Minister’s own local authority area, West Oxfordshire, has seen a per capita increase of £57.23, whereas my own local authority, for example, has seen a reduction of £354.13.  One area that is affluent has seen an increase; an area that is less affluent has seen a massive reduction
